org.safs.xml
Class MultiLogResults

java.lang.Object
  org.safs.xml.MultiLogResults

public class MultiLogResults
extends java.lang.Object

Processes a user-specified directory for XML files. Creates a new single XML file consolidating the file hrefs for all XML files in the directory. Optionally, creates a summary XML file containing:

  • For each XML file that proves to be a SAFS XML Log the class will:

    1. Record the log file href information uniquely identifying the log
    2. Record the date/time the log was opened
    3. Record the final status report information for that log
    4. Maintain an cumulative summary of all status report information for all files
    5. Record the date/time the log was closed

  • Record the cumulative summary of all status report information from all files

JVM Arguments:

  • -Dsafs.multilog.dir="<path/to/xmllogs/directory>"
    Full path to the directory containing the SAFS XML log(s) to consolidate and/or summarize.
    Ex: -Dsafs.multilog.dir="C:\SAFS\Project\Datapool\Logs"
    Same as command-line argument: -dir "C:\SAFS\Project\Datapool\Logs"

  • -Dsafs.multilog.out="<path/to/output/directory>"
    Full path to the directory where any generated files will be written. By default all generated files will be written to the same directory where input files are found.
    Ex: -Dsafs.multilog.out="C:\SAFS\Project\Reports"
    Same as command-line argument: -out "C:\SAFS\Project\Reports"

  • -Dsafs.multilog.log="<path/to/single/safsxmllog.xml>"
    Full or relative path to a single SAFS XML log to summarize.
    Ex: -Dsafs.multilog.log="C:\SAFS\Project\Datapool\Logs\TestComposerLog.xml"
    Ex: -Dsafs.multilog.log="TestComposerLog.xml"
    Same as command-line argument: -log "TestComposerLog.xml"

  • -Dsafs.multilog.nosummary
    If present, only the initial XML list file containing the file hrefs for all SAFS XML log files will be created. All subsequent processing will be aborted.
    Same as command-line argument: -nosummary

  • -Dsafs.multilog.summary="<path/to/xml/summary.xml>"
    Full or relative path to a summary XML file to process.
    Ex: -Dsafs.multilog.summary="C:\SAFS\Project\Reports\EMinerSummary.xml"
    Ex: -Dsafs.multilog.summary="EMinerSummary.xml"
    Same as command-line argument: -summary "EMinerSummary.xml"

  • -Dsafs.multilog.noupdate
    If present, no attempt to update the data should occur. Same as command-line argument: -noupdate

  • -Dsafs.multilog.dataid="<data_id>"
    The data id to be used in our connection queries and updates.
    Ex: -Dsafs.multilog.dataidt="mydata"
    Same as command-line argument: -dataid "mydata"

  • -Dsafs.multilog.datapath="<data_path>"
    The data path to be associated with the data_id.
    Ex: -Dsafs.multilog.datapath="'/tst/tools/deploymentdetails/shrdata'"
    Same as command-line argument: -datapath "/tst/tools/deploymentdetails/shrdata"

  • -Dsafs.multilog.where="<where_clause>"
    The where clause to filter the queries and updates.
    Ex: -Dsafs.multilog.where="ticketid = 123456"
    Same as command-line argument: -where "ticketid = 123456"

  • -Dsafs.multilog.dataset="<dataset_id>"
    The dataset id to be updated in the reports database.
    Ex: -Dsafs.multilog.dataset="zdeployment"
    Same as command-line argument: -dataset "zdeployment"

  • -Dsafs.multilog.field="<field_id>"
    The field id to be updated in the reports database.
    Ex: -Dsafs.multilog.field="entminer"
    Same as command-line argument: -field "entminer"

  • -Dsafs.multilog.value="<value>"
    The value to be updated into the field in the reports database.
    Ex: -Dsafs.multilog.value="SUCCESS"
    Same as command-line argument: -value "SUCCESS"

  • -Dsafs.multilog.connection="<connection_uri>"
    The value to be used for the JDBC database connection.
    Ex: -Dsafs.multilog.connection="sharenet://qashr05:port"
    Same as command-line argument: -connection "sharenet://qashr05:port"

  • -Dsafs.multilog.connection.props="<name=value;name=value>"
    Zero or more name=value pairs (separated by semi-colons) to be used during the connection request.
    This argument can appear more than once, if needed.
    Ex: -Dsafs.multilog.connection.props="undoPolicyNone=True"
    Same as command-line argument: -props "undoPolicyNone=True"

  • -Dsafs.multilog.opsource="<text identifying update source>"
    Text to be remotely logged identifying the source of this update request.
    Ex: -Dsafs.multilog.opsource="Support:Carl Nagle:org.safs.xml.MultiLogResults.java"
    Same as command-line argument: -opsource "Support:Carl Nagle:org.safs.xml.MultiLogResults.java"

  • -Dsafs.multilog.drivers="<driverclass1;driverclass2>"
    Zero or more jdbc driver class names to append to the jdbc.drivers System property, separated by semi-colons.
    Ex: -Dsafs.multilog.drivers="com.sas.net.sharenet.ShareNetDriver"
    Same as command-line argument: -drivers "com.sas.net.sharenet.ShareNetDriver"

This class requires the JDBC Drivers for SAS/Share be in the CLASSPATH already. This generally means that both associated JAR files be in the System CLASSPATH ( or passed in the command-line):

  • sas.core.jar
  • sas.intrnet.javatools.jar
